## Preparing Your Application (Form 101-09)

If AAA doesn't cover your site, you'll need to submit [Form 101-09](https://www.casa.gov.au/sites/default/files/2021-03/application-rpa-flight-authorisation-area-approval-permission-form-101-09.pdf) (always check the [CASA website](https://www.casa.gov.au) for the latest version).

Get your evidence pack together *before* you open the form.

### Airspace and Planning Checks

- [ ] Confirm the airspace classification and any restrictions at your site
- [ ] Verify with aviation charts (VTC/VNC/PCA) and the ERSA entry for the nearest aerodrome
- [ ] Confirm operational details and location with clients

### Documents to Attach

- [ ] Updated RPAS Operations Manual
- [ ] Updated RPAS Operational Procedure (from your procedure library)
- [ ] Completed Flight Authorisation form (from your Ops Manual)
- [ ] Job Safety Assessment (JSA) — include a map/screenshot showing TOL sites, observer positions, exclusion zones, safe zones, signage
- [ ] Risk Assessment (RA) — specific to this mission, not a generic template
- [ ] Site coordinates and maps (lat/long in aviation format, KMZ file)
- [ ] Aeronautical Radio Operator Certificate (AROC)

### Additional Documents (If Applicable)

- [ ] Landowner, council or facility manager permissions
- [ ] Letter of Agreement (LOA) for Defence-oversighted aerodromes
- [ ] BVLOS Concept of Operations (ConOps) document

### If Operating Near/Inside a CTR

- [ ] VHF radio capability confirmed
- [ ] ATC coordination plan documented (who to call, when, standing instructions)
- [ ] NAIPS login available for briefings and any NOTAM coordination

### Record-Keeping

Your records system must be able to demonstrate planning evidence on audit — compliant with AIP and Part 101 MOS, with 7-year retention and a backup plan. If your records system goes down with no backup, you must cease operations until it's restored.

