## After Approval: What Happens Next

Once CASA grants your approval, you'll receive an instrument document specifying:

- The approved area and conditions
- Valid dates (e.g., 1 May 2025 – 1 May 2027)
- Approved frequency of operations (e.g., once per month)
- Any specific conditions you must comply with

**Read the instrument carefully.** Your operations must stay within the scope and conditions listed.

---

## Pre-Operation Checklist

Before each flight under your approval:

- [ ] Complete/update your Flight Plan, Risk Assessment and JSA for the specific operation
- [ ] CRP signs off on the documentation (check your Operations Manual for internal procedures)
- [ ] If in a DJI geofenced zone — submit a GeoZone unlock request at least 2–3 business days before the flight and confirm access is granted (you won't be able to take off without it)
- [ ] Submit a NOTAM to CASA at least 2 business days before the flight if required by your approval conditions, and confirm it's active
- [ ] On the day — check weather, confirm the NOTAM is active, and verify NOTAMs from other operators in the area
- [ ] Pre-plan your flight route in the remote controller where possible to save time on site
- [ ] After the flight — export files from the drone and process in your chosen software

---

## Key Takeaways

- **ReOC holders only** — without a ReOC, you can't apply for these approvals
- **Check AAA first** — if your site is near a trial location, automated authorisation saves significant time and money
- **Plan early** — Form 101-09 applications take up to 70 days, so submit well ahead of your intended operation date
- **Prepare thoroughly** — a clean, complete application with all supporting documents reduces back-and-forth with CASA
- **Comply with conditions** — once approved, your operations must stay within the scope of the instrument

